Commentary.Commentary: It is time for the West Indian batters to have a go with the blade now. It will be Kraigg Brathwaite and Tagenarine Chanderpaul to open for the visitors. The Australian players stride out to the middle as well. It will be Mitchell Starc to start with the new ball. Here we go...
... SECOND INNINGS ...

Right then. Australia have decided to declare now and will have a bite of the pink ball before the Tea break. Nothing much happened with the blade for Aussies in the second session on Day 2, as they kept losing intervals at regular intervals. Alex Carey was the only one who managed to stay out at the crease and take the score above 500. West Indies though came in with the right intent after the post-Dinner session. They did really well to put a lid on the run rate and frustrate the Australian batters. The onus now is on the batters to remain unscathed in the remaining session before they head back to the pavilion for Tea. Stick around to find out how things pan out.
Fuller, on off, driven to covers. Three dots on the trot to end the over. The signal comes from the pavilion and Mitchell Starc and Carey are running off the field here. Australia declare at 511-7.
Back of a length, outside off. Carey lets it be.
It is full, wide of off. Alex Carey throws the kitchen sink at it but connects with thin air. He is having a go here, with the shadows coming into play now.
FOUR! Alex Carey gets his second boundary of the over and moves into 40s. Joseph goes full, on fourth stump. Alex Carey belts it past mid off. It races away.
Alex Carey stays back to this full delivery and nudges it to short mid-wicket.
FOUR! Incredible shot! It is full, wide of off. Carey leans in and drives it on the up. The ball races through the gap at covers for four runs.
Much fuller, attacking the pads. Starc hangs back and clips it through mid-wicket for two runs.
Loops it up, on off, defended out.
Another single now as this is flicked to mid on.
Loops it up, on middle and leg. Starc flicks it to the left of mid on and crosses. This also brings up 500 for the Aussies.
Full and on off, Starc pushes it out.
On off, blocked out.

Anderson Phillip very nearly gets a wicket here. A length ball, wide of off. Carey decides to play it late and hangs his blade away from his body. The ball takes the outside edge but does not carry to the man at first slip.
A length ball, at 134 clicks, outside off. Carey leans in and times it well. The batters take two before the fielder cuts it out. Carey wanted the third run but was sent back in no time.
FOUR! Up and over! Back of a length, on off. Carey stands tall and heaves it across the line for a boundary at deep mid-wicket. He moves to 30 now.
Much fuller, on middle and leg. Carey whips it to the right of short mid-wicket.
Anderson Phillip comes 'round the wicket and angles a full delivery into the pads. Starc stays inside the crease and glances around the corner for a single.
Back of a length, wide of off. Carey hangs back and cuts it through point for one run.
Tossed up, turning down leg. Carey flicks it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Mitchell Starc gets off the mark instantly as he drives this full delivery to long on for one.

OUT! LBW! Kraigg Brathwaite appeals for lbw and the umpire raises his finger in a flash. Michael Neser thinks it is pitching outside leg and takes the review. The delivery is full and around middle, coming in with the arm. Neser looks to sweep it away but misses and takes a blow on his pads. The Snicko confirms that there is clear day-light between bat and ball. The Ball Tracking later confirms that it is umpire's call on ball hitting the wickets. Australia don't lose a review here but surely lose their man. Mitchell Starc is the new man at the crease.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Kraigg Brathwaite

Drinks break! West Indies have been quite solid with the ball in the post-Dinner session. They have picked up two wickets so far and would be hoping to get a couple more before the end of the session. Alex Carey is the only recognised batter at the crease for the Aussies and he surely holds the key for them. Australia might also be thinking about declaring before the twilight comes into play. Should be interesting to see which path they take. An enticing passage of play awaits.

OUT! CHOPPED ON! Alzarri Joseph strikes this time and sends the struggling Cameron Green back to the pavilion. West Indies get their second wicket in the second session on Day 2. They are crawling back into this game now. It is a length ball, on fifth stump. Cameron Green moves across but decides to leave it in the end. Although, he is a tad late into pulling his bat away. The ball takes the inner half and goes on to rattle the stumps behind.
Commentary.Howout: b Alzarri Joseph

OUT! RUN OUT! Travis Head has to walk back on 175 here. He gets a standing ovation on his way back but he will be extremely guttted. Just what the doctor ordered for West Indies here. They need a couple more now with two new batters out on the crease. This is tossed up, on leg stump. Cameron Green stays back and flicks it towards fine leg. The big screen shows out. Devon Thomas is the man who is quick to react in the field. Alex Carey is the new man in.

We are back for the second session on Day 2. So then, Travis Head is the set-batsman out on the crease at the moment and is just 28 runs short of his double century. Cameron Green strides out along with him. The West Indies players also take the field. They will be hunting for some early wickets in this session, if they are to make inroads in this game. It will be Roston Chase to get us underway with the ball in this session. Here we go...
... Day 2, Session 2 ...

The West Indies bowlers are trying hard to find their lengths right but just cannot find them. Devon Thomas did manage to get one wicket at the very end of this session but they are way behind in this game as of now. They have hardly seemed to have troubled Australian batters and they will need to work hard to make their way back into the game. Australia will continue to bat and the West Indies bowlers will have to try out something new if they need to bag some early wickets in the second session. Can they do it? Or will the Aussies continue to bat freely? We shall find out shortly. Do join us at 12.10 pm IST (6.40 am GMT) post dinner.

SESSION SUMMARY - 28 overs, 106 runs, and 1 wicket. The first session of Day 2 of this pink ball is done and dusted and it is still the hosts who are in the driver's seat. Another great day for the Aussies as they pile up 106 runs for the loss of just one wicket. They started the day at 330 for 3 wickets and Marnus Labuschagne and Travis Head were batting with ease. West Indies did manage to get the wicket of the run machine in the very end but the local boy, Travis Head hardly seems to be troubled. He continued to bat on despite the loss of his partner as Green walked out to the middle to bat for the first time in the series. They will look to build up another mammoth partnership now.

We are all set for the game to resume. West Indies players make their way out in the middle. Marnus Labuschagne and Travis Head will continue to bat for Australia. Jason Holder comes to bowl. Here we go.

West Indies were down and drained, as they needed to use 7 bowlers to complete the first day. Alzarri Joseph, Jason Holder, and Devon Thomas were the successful bowlers, with all picking a wicket each. They will need to start off well and bag some early wickets in the first session of Day 2. Can they do it? We will find out shortly.

David Warner and Usman Khawaja started off well but Warner fell into the trap of Alzarri Joseph and Labuschage came in. Khwahja departed for 62. Holder soon after got the skipper for a duck and then came in the local boy, Travis Head. Head and Labuschagne brewed a partnership of 199 runs and the scoreboard stands 330/3 as of now.

Hello and a warm welcome to the Day 2 of the West Indies tour of Australia. The hosts will be the ones who have had better sleep and the visitors will be busy making the strategies. Day 1 saw 89 overs, and 330 runs for the loss of just 3 wickets.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, that is all we have from this opening day of the second Test match which has been pretty one-sided. West Indies have loads of work to do on Day 2 if they are to claw themselves back into this game. Will we witness a fightback from the visitors? Or will Australia consolidate their position even further? We shall find out when the play resumes on Friday, 9th of December at 9.30 am IST (4 am GMT). Do join us for the build-up which begins well in advance. Cheers!

West Indies got off to a decent start early in the day when Alzarri Joseph dismissed David Warner cheaply on what seems like a great batting surface. The visitors suffered another injury blow as Marquino Mindley hobbled off injured on his debut. A 95-run partnership between Usman Khawaja and Marnus Labuschagne steadied the ship for Australia but the former was dismissed by Devon Thomas after he got to his half-century. Jason Holder dismissed the Australian skipper Steven Smith on a duck but after that, it has been all about Marnus Labuschagne and Travis Head. Australia will look to continue and bat most of the day to take the possibility of a loss out of the equation. West Indies need early wickets and with the ball pretty new, it will be interesting to see if the fast bowlers get some purchase.

Australia came out for the last session with Marnus Labuschagne and Travis Head looking to build on their partnership and they began watchfully initially. Marnus Labuschagne continued to score at a steady pace and got to his third century in a row remaining unbeaten on 120. Travis Head played the role of an aggressor and accumulated runs at a quicker pace scoring 114 in 139 balls. Eventually, they went into stumps having put on a 199-run partnership in 280 balls and as mentioned by Marnus Labuschagne in the Tea break, it is quite evident they enjoy playing with each other. West Indies lacked any sort of penetration and with a lack of a frontline spinner in their ranks, they could not utilize the old ball. They did take the new ball immediately but could not make an impact with it so far.

SESSION SUMMARY - 34 overs, 141 runs, and 0 wickets. Another session which was dominated by the Australian batters and West Indies lacked any sort of creativity to be able to get a breakthrough. Two centurions in their ranks and they are still unbeaten as they put together a chanceless partnership to make this a day that belongs to the hosts. West Indies have their work cut out in this Test match and with the way their shoulders had dropped in this session, it is clear in which direction this game is headed.

We are back for the final session of Day 1. West Indies players make their way out in the middle. Marnus Labuschagne and Travis Head willl continue to bat. Alzarri Joseph to bowl. Here we go.

Right then, we will return for the final session of Day 1 shortly and there is still loads of work to be done by both teams. Australia will be looking to make this partnership between Marnus Labuschagne and Travis Head count. West Indies, on the other hand, have to take early wickets and try to end the day on a high. Which way will this tie turn? We will know really soon.

Marnus Labuschagne is in for a quick chat. He says that it is disappointing to lose a couple of wickets but it is great to bat here with Travis Head. Adds that it's nice to keep up the scoreboard ticking. Ends by saying that it is important to believe in the process and he is happy where they are placed at this stage.

West Indies will be thrilled with the fact that they have claimed two crucial wickets on a pitch that has very little to offer to the bowlers. Devon Thomas bowled well and claimed a wicket to break a dangerous partnership that was brewing and Jason Holder got one in his kitty. What would disappoint them though is the fact that they were unable to maintain the pressure thereafter and bowled too many loose balls due to their eagerness to claim wickets. There will need to be patient and disciplined if they are to get ahead in this game.

SESSION SUMMARY - 27 overs, 100 runs, and 2 wickets. This has been a session that both teams will be both happy with but will know that they could have done better. Australia looked solid after the Dinner break but the dismissal of Usman Khawaja after a 95-run partnership with Marnus Labuschagne and the captain Steven Smith soon after took away their momentum slightly. Marnus Labuschagne continued his rich rein of form as he is well on course to score his third century in this series in as many innings. He is building a good partnership with Travis Head as they have put on 58 runs in 74 balls.

We are set for the game to resume. The umpires make their way out to the middle and so do the players of West Indies. Usman Khawaja and Marnus Labuschagne stride out to the middle to resume their partnership. Anderson Phillip will begin proceedings after the break. Let's go...
... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...

Both teams had a few injury worries and made some alterations to their starting lineups. Steven Smith choose to bat first and probably was the right decision. Usman Khawaja scored a half-century and he will be hoping to carry on with the momentum. Marnus Labuschagne looks good and is batting with ease. Kraigg Brathwaite will want his bowlers to find their length right and get timely breakthroughs in the game. West Indies have some work to do here. Will they get some early breakthroughs in the second session? Or will the Aussie batters continue to bat freely and keep the scoreboard ticking? We shall find out soon. Do join us at 12.10 pm IST (6:40 am GMT) post dinner.

SESSION SUMMARY - 28 overs, 89 runs, and 1 wicket. So the first session of the Pink Ball Test is done and dusted, with Australia scoring 89 runs for the loss of 1 wicket. The wicket was of David Warner, who fell in the trap set by Alzarri Joseph. Post Warner's dismissal, in walked Marnus Labuschagne and stitched a good partnership with Khawaja to ensure that Australia have the upper hand post dinner. The Windies' bowling didn't really look like a problem to deal with for the Aussie batters, Usman Khawaja and Marnus Labuschagne after that.

Who will walk out now?

David Warner walks out at 21.

Starts with a length ball outside off, 133.9 kph. David Warner knocks it to extra covers. The fielder has a long chase to do. They collect three runs.

We are set for the game to begin. The umpires have made their way out to the middle followed by the West Indies players who take their position on the field. David Warner and Usman Khawaja will open the inning for Australia. The players take a knee in support of the BLM movement. Alzarri Joseph has been handed the new ball and he will begin proceedings. Let's play...

West Indies (Playing XI) - Kraigg Brathwaite (C), Tagenarine Chanderpaul, Shamarh Brooks (In for Nkrumah Bonner), Jermaine Blackwood, Devon Thomas (In for Kyle Mayers), Jason Holder, Joshua Da Silva (WK), Roston Chase, Alzarri Joseph, Anderson Phillip (In for Kemar Roach), Marquino Mindley (In for Jayden Seales).

Australia (Playing XI) - David Warner, Usman Khawaja, Marnus Labuschagne, Steven Smith (C), Travis Head, Cameron Green, Alex Carey (WK), Michael Neser (In for Josh Hazlewood), Mitchell Starc, Nathan Lyon, Scott Boland (In for Pat Cummins).
TOSS - Australia have won the toss and will BAT first.

On the contrary, the visitors did show some fight and started off well in the first innings. Chanderpaul was dismissed for 51 in the first game and the wickets kept on tumbling for the visitors after that. Brathwaite was their lone warrior throughout the game. Their bowling unit was much more worse as they failed to pick wickets at regular intervals. They will definitely look to bounce back and level the series. Can they do it? Let's find out. Stay tuned for toss and other updates.

The hosts were ruthless with the bat and the ball. Labuschagne and Smith were the picks of the batters for them. Both of them scored a double century in the first innings and Labuschagne scored a hundred in the second innings as well. In the bowling unit, Starc and Cummins bagged three each in the first innings whilst Lyon rattled the visitors with a six-wicket haul in the second. Cummins is ruled out by an injury in this game and it will be interesting to see how the team performs under Smith.

Hello and a warm welcome for the final test of the two-match series at Adelaide. It is a must-win game for the visitors as a loss or a draw will hand them a series defeat. They will look to bounce back and win this tine whilst the hosts will look to clean sweep the series.
... MATCH DAY ...

We are all set for the game to resume. West Indies players have made their way out in the middle. David Warner and Usman Khawaja are the openers for the Aussies. Alzarri Joseph comes to bowl. Here we go.
... DAY 3, SESSION 2 ...

Right then, Australia will come to bat again, and the follow-on hasn't been implemented. They will look to extend their lead and post another mammoth total for the visitors. Will the visitors start on a fresh note and get some early wickets post dinner? Or will the Aussies continue to bat freely and post another huge total for the Windies? We shall find out shortly.

West Indies were sloppy from the start and they lost two early wickets in the first session of Day 3. A couple of wickets were lost due to their own haphazardness and one of them was a set batter, Tagenarine Chanderpaul. Anderson Phillip and Tagenarine Chanderpaul did steady the ship for a while and were brewing a good partnership, but after Tagenarine Chanderpaul was dismissed by the run-out error, wickets just kept on tumbling for the Windies and there was no turning back. Roston Chase and Marquino Mindley did give some fight in the end and they got many lifelines. The dropped catches didn't help them and the home side will be relatively pleased with how things worked out for them.

An excellent display with the ball from the Aussies as they managed to take 6 wickets in the first session of Day 3. Mitchell Starc gave them a perfect start and bagged two wickets in his first two overs. Nathan Lyon joined the party afterward as they managed to bundle the West Indies at just 214 runs. They are well in control of the game from the start and will hope to carry on with the momentum and clean sweep this series. They now lead by a mammoth 297 runs and will be hoping to extend their lead.

OUT! TAKEN! Mitchell Starc gets the last wicket finally. Fuller and on off, Roston Chase looks to use the pace of the ball and flick it but mistimes it completely. The ball goes up in the air towards deep backward square leg. Nathan Lyon takes a good catch diving forward and West Indies are bundled out for 214 runs! That will be DINNER on Day 3.
Commentary.Howout: c Nathan Lyon b Mitchell Starc

Alex Carey is aware of it and takes an excellent catch diving to his right. A dream start for Mitchell Starc and Australia here an they have two early wickets inside the first three overs!

Fuller and on off, Anderson Phillip defends it solidly off his front foot.
Tosses it up outside off, Anderson Phillip leaves it alone.

OUT! RUN OUT! A huge mix-up and Tagenarine Chanderpaul has to make his way back into the hut. A perfect start for Australia. On a length and on off, Tagenarine Chanderpaul taps it to the leg side and calls for one but Anderson Phillip sends him back from half way. Mitchell Starc is quick enough to get towards the ball as he makes a direct hit. The decision is sent upstairs. Replay shows that Tagenarine Chanderpaul was just out of his crease and Australia have an early breakthrough right at the start of Day 3! Jason Holder walks in next.
Commentary.Howout: run out (Mitchell Starc)

Commentary.Commentary: Bangs a shorter one, Tagenarine Chanderpaul ducks underneath it.
Good length and on leg as he comes 'round the wicket, Tagenarine Chanderpaul defends it to square leg.
Starts with a shorter one outside leg, Tagenarine Chanderpaul lets it go.

We are all set for the game to begin. Australian players and the umpires make their way out in the middle. Anderson Phillip and Tagenarine Chanderpaul will continue to bat. Mitchell Starc to start with the ball. Here we go.

West Indies openers Kraigg Brathwaite and Tagenarine Chanderpaul, yet again started off well and batted out good adding 35 runs. Once they lost their skipper, the wickets kept on tumbling for them. Trailing by a huge margin, Tagenarine Chanderpaul stood firm and is playing a special knock of 47 off 98 deliveries. He will hope to keep on batting and keep the scoreboard ticking for the West Indies. Can the visitors bat their way and pull a rabbit out of the hat on Day 3? Stay tuned to find out.

Steven Smith declared the Australian innings at 511/7 after 137 overs. A special knock from Marnus Labuschagne and Travis Head made them reach to a mammoth total. Once they declared, the plan was clear for them, to bag as many wickets as possible at the end of Day 2. They managed to get 4 wickets as Michael Neser took two and Lyon and Green took one each. They will hope to take some early wickets at the start now.

Hello and a warm welcome to the first session of the Day 3 of West Indies tour of Australia. The first two days were dominated by the hosts and they are in the drivers seat at the moment. The Windies will have to do something special to make their way back into the game. West Indies are at 102/4 after 37 overs and they still trail by 409 runs.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Australia certainly have an upper hand in this fixture and will surely be coming on with an intention of killing the game as early as possible. West Indies batters certainly have their task cut out and cannot afford any errors at this stage. The action continues on 10th December as the Day 3 begins at 9.30 am IST (4 am GMT). But as you all know you can join us early for the build-up. Cheers!

It was a special knock from Tagenarine Chanderpaul that has kept them in the game so far. West Indies have all their hopes on this newcomer when they come back to bat on Day 3. The youngster hardly found an able partner at the other end, as Nathan Lyon and Cameron Green rubbed salt on the wounds with a wicket each. Although Anderson Phillip in the end, did enough to see off the Day's play.

Australia declared at 511/7 before having a shy with the ball at the brink of Tea. They could not find any success in the limited amount of time in hand, although the scenario changed completely in the post-Tea session. It was the brilliance of Neser that caused an upset for West Indies as he picked two in quick succession to hurt the visitors.
Right then, it is Australia who end the proceedings of Day 2 on a high. West Indies were unable to keep the Australian bowlers at bay in the final session here. The visitors still trail by 409 runs.
A length ball, wide of off. Anderson Phillip negotiates the final delivery by defending it into the deck. THAT WILL BE STUMPS ON DAY 2.
A sharp bouncer on middle. Anderson Phillip ducks under it safely.
Length ball, on middle and leg. Anderson Phillip defends it out solidly.
Fuller, on off. Anderson Phillip presses forward and blocks it out.
A length ball, that lands outside off and jags back in a long way. Anderson Phillip shoulders his arms at it and takes a blow near his waist.
Cameron Green goes full, on middle and leg. Anderson Phillip gets his blade down in time. Another no ball for Green. He needs to be careful with his landing.
A short ball, on off. Tagenarine Chanderpaul pulls it hard to the leg side. Travis Head takes a blow over his knees here and allows the batters to only cross for one.
Fuller, attacking the stumps. Anderson Phillip presses forward and blocks it out.

Good length, outside off, this one nips in off the deck. Anderson Phillip defends it out solidly.

It is full, on middle and leg. Anderson Phillip defends it to mid on.
Back of a length, on fourth stump. Tagenarine Chanderpaul dabs it down to third man for one. 100 is up for the visitors now.
A short ball, on off. Tagenarine Chanderpaul pulls it hard to mid-wicket. Marnus Labuschagne kills the pace by getting a hand on it. The batters take one.
A dot now as this length ball is played towards mid-wicket.
A single now as this is flicked behind square on the leg side.
Outside off, left alone. The umpire signals a no ball for overstepping.

In the air, but it lands safely! It is a short ball, on the bodyline. This one gets big on Chanderpaul. He gets a thick outside edge and the ball flies towards fine leg. The two fielders in the deep try to converge but it lands in between them.
Green dishes a sharp bouncer, on middle. Tagenarine Chanderpaul ducks under it safely.
Tagenarine Chanderpaul mistimes his pull shot this time to square leg.
Good length, wide of off. Anderson Phillip steps forward and shoulders his arms at it.

Fuller in length, on off. Anderson Phillip blocks it behind point.

FOUR! Up and over! It is much fuller, angled across the left-hander. Tagenarine Chanderpaul gets under it and lofts it over covers for an exceptional boundary.
A length ball, on off, Tagenarine Chanderpaul is solid in his defense.
Back of a length, on fifth stump, left alone.

OUT! CHOPPED ON! West Indies lose their fourth wicket now. Cameron Green strikes and finds an important breakthrough here. Australia are on top in this game. It is a length ball, on fourth stump. Devon Thomas tries to chase it but without any foot movement. He ends up dragging it on his own stumps. Cameron Green has turned this expensive over into a fruitful one. Anderson Phillip is the new man at the crease now.
Commentary.Howout: b Cameron Green

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Nicely played! It is fuller, wide of off. Thomas leans in and carves it behind point for four runs.
A single now as Tagenarine Chanderpaul mistimes his pull to deep square leg.

FOUR! Incredible shot! Back of a length, on off. Tagenarine Chanderpaul pulls it in front of the man at mid-wicket. He hits it along the ground as well to fnd the boundary. Another no ball for overstepping.

The Snicko confirms that there is no bat on it, as it comes off the pads. Later, Australia lose a review and Devon Thomas gain some more time at the crease.

They will need to build up a solid partnership if they need to get back in the game. Australian bowlers are finding their lengths right and getting timely breakthroughs. Mitchell Starc comes into the attack now.

It is now time for the final session on Day 2 as the sun goes down. Kraigg Brathwaite and Tagenarine Chanderpaul are out at the crease. The Australian players have also taken the field. It will be Scott Boland to start with the ball this time.
... Day 2, Session 3 ...

West Indies have had a successful outing so far, as they have managed remain unscathed in the short time they spent at the crease. Australian bowlers had only 5 overs to bowl before the Tea break but could not create any clear-cut opportunities to hurt West Indies. In the opening hour of second session, Australia could not continue on their merry way with Head beind perished through a shabby run out. Later, no other batter except Alex Carey could get going. Eventually, the Aussies declared at 511/7 with the tail-enders in play. It was a really good decision to declare early and have a go with the ball but it did not pay off yet. Mitchell Starc and Scott Boland are the two bowlers used so far. The Australian bowlers will be coming back into the final session with an intention of causing immense trouble with the conditions on offer. An all-important session awaits. Do join us at 2.30 pm IST (9 am GMT) to find out how things pan out.

We are all set for the game to begin. Australia players ake their way out in the middle. Tagenarine Chanderpaul and Kraigg Brathwaite are the openers for the West Indies. Mitchell Starc comes to bowl. Here we go.
... FOURTH INNINGS ...

Earlier in the day, West Indies were bowled out for just 214 runs. Australia bowlers were right on the money where Mitchell Starc and Michael Neser took two wickets Whilst Nathan Lyon took three. They will be hoping for the same performance now from heir bowlers. Can they get some quick wickets at the end of the day? Or will the West Indies openers bat till the end? Lets find out soon.

And with Alex Carey's wicket, Steven Smith calls his team back and they have declared. They scored quick 199 runs adding to their scoreboard and the target is now 497. Steven Smith will be happy with the team's performance as they scored 199 runs in just 31 overs and now they will be hoping for their bowlers to bag some early wickets. West Indies will be hoping for their openers to play out for the Day and not lose any of the wickets at the end of Day 3.

... DAY 3, SESSION 3 ...

Right then, the hosts are still in the driver's seat and are well in control of the game. They lead by 433 and will be eyeing on that magical 500 run mark or maybe more. Will they continue to bat till the end of the session? Or will they declare soon? Let's find out shortly.

Woah! This session has been quite enticing. The Australia batters certainly put their foot down and aimed to score briskly. Usman Khawaja and David Warner started brilliantly and built a solid platform up top, although they could not continue on their merry way as Roston Chase got rid of both of them in his very first over. This though did not put a lid over the run-rate as Steven Smith came out with an attacking intent and managed to find boundaries at will. Marnus Labuschagne though slipped out right at the brink of Tea. West Indies have managed to take three big wickets but their bowlers have their task cut out for the final session of the day. Australia have a lead of 433 runs and have a stronger hold over this game. West Indies need some sort of miracle if they are to make a comeback in this game.

Right then, that is all we have from this fascinating Test series of the West Indies tour of Australia. Steven Smith lifts up the trophy and the Aussies clean sweep the series 2-0. West Indies now have some rest for a while but the Aussies have their next assignment in place with a Test series lined up against South Africa. It starts on 17th December at 5:50 am IST (12:20 am GMT) which will be played The Gabba, Brisbane. But as you know, our build-up begins much earlier so do join us for the same. Till then, goodbye and cheers!

Steven Smith, the victorious captain is in for a chat. He says that it was a nice toss to win and praises the batters for their effort on Day 1. Informs everyone is contributing when they need to. They have a lot of trust among eachother and that helps a lot. Says Marnus Labuschagne works really hard in the nets and is really adaptable. Hence it is not surprising to see him play really well. Mentions that it is great to see Michael Neser to come in and have a great impact as well. Says that there is a lot of competition for spots in the team and this is what makes it more exciting. Mentions that South Africa present a really good challenge for them and they surely need to bring their A-game against the Proteas.. Ends by saying that he is surely enjoying the captaincy.

Kraigg Brathwaite, the skipper of West Indies says that it is disappointing for sure. Says that for the first game they showed some fight but in the second they were outplayed. Adds that they had some injury concerns which had a hand in this big defeat and they need to continue to work hard. Applauds Tagenarine Chanderpaul and says that he looks like a bright future for West Indies cricket. Ends by saying that the fans will like to see them win and they will keep on working for that.

Marnus Labuschagne wins the Player of the Series for racking up more than 500 runs over two matches. He says that it nice to be going through a nice patch with scoring aplenty and the teams winning run as well. Adds that at the moment they have already started focusing on the future series but he really enjoyed to bat over this one. Mentions, it takes some time to find the rhythm in a pink-ball game but likes how it is going for him. Adds that he just focuses on being in the moment and do well for the team. Informs he is surely looking forward to the next challenge against South Africa.

The local boy, Travis Head is adjudged as the Man of the Match for his incredible innings of 175 runs. He says that it was a brilliant week and he is looking forward to the next week. Adds that it is a beautiful feeling and he did his things well. Praises Marnus Labuschagne for his excellent innings. Ends by saying that he feels lucky to play here and the credit goes to the entire team for winning this one.
Stay tuned for the presentation...

Mitchell Starc comes in for a quick chat. He says it was a great team effort and everyone contributed to the victory. Adds that there were some individual efforts to appreciate as well and Pat Cummins is recovering and he will join them soon. Further says that Steven Smith is doing good in what he does he says that he just loves to watch Marnus Labuschagne bat and he does it great.

In the third innings, Australia came in with an intent of attacking the bowlers from the word go. They envisioned to get the target over 500 but it did not go as per their plan as they kept losing wickets at regular intervals and eventually declared at 199/6. Which meant that West Indies had a steep target to climb which read 497. It was Alzarri Joseph who managed to put some batters under pressure with his seam bowling. During the chase, West Indies were on the back foot straightaway as they were teetering at 21/4. Later, it took Australia just a single session on Day 4 to take the remaining wickets in hand and bowl out West Indies for just 77 runs to record an outstanding victory. Australia used only 4 bowlers during the chase - Mitchell Starc, Michael Neser, Scott Boland and Nathan Lyon. Wherein the seamers returned with three wickets each and Lyon picked a sole wicket.

West Indies though struggled to get going with the blade. Only Tagenarine Chanderpaul stood out for them with 47 in their first innings. West Indies surely need some thinking to do with their batting combination. Apart from the opener, it was Anderson Phillip's 43 that got them to 214 but it was way too short than what the Aussies managed to post on the board. It was the GOAT, Nathan Lyon who stood out with the ball for the hosts with his three-fer.

Looking back at how things went down - It was Australia that decided to bat first and took the game away from the visitors in the first innings itself as they scored a mammoth total of 511. Usman Khawaja set the tone with the blade up top. Later, it was a special knock from Marnus Labuschagne (163) and Travis Head (175). Both fell agonisingly short of their double ton but nonetheless the damage was already done. It was Alex Carey who played a brisk knock of 41 runs to help his side cross the 500-run mark. West Indies had to toil hard and found it difficult to put the pressure on the opposition.

Coming into Day 4, Australia needed only 6 wickets to seal the victory and boy they did not waste any time at all. It was Mitchell Starc who opened the floodgates with two quick wickets of Devon Thomas and Jason Holder. Later, it was the brilliance of Alex Carey behind the sticks and the captaincy of Steven Smith that made sure Australia get closer to the finish line quickly. The Aussies were finding it difficult to break the gritty stand of Chase and Da Silva, but once the stand was broken, Australia took out the tail in a jiffy.

That was too easy for the Aussies and they have wrapped up the series 2-0! The Aussies have certainly outclassed the visitors on both the Test matches played over the series. Australia were right on the front foot from the first ball on Day 4.

We are all set for the first session of Day 4 to begin. The Aussies have made their way out in the middle. Devon Thomas and Jason Holder will continue to bat for the Windies. Mitchell Starc comes to bowl. Here we go.

The visitors will have to come up with something magical here if they need to stay in the game. They have lost four wickets with both their openers back in the hut. Devon Thomas and Jason Holder did show some intent and defended till the 22nd over after they were 21/4 inside just 9 overs. The Aussies do have the game under their control and they have done it with much dominance. Can they continue to do it? Or will the visitors come up with something magical here? Let's find out shortly.

The Aussies after bowling out West Indies didn't give them a follow-on. They just came out and ran a havoc over the West Indies bowlers and scored 199 runs in 31 overs. As soon as they had a comfortable lead in the game, Steven Smith declared their innings. Scott Boland bowled a special sixth over in the game where he bagged three wickets. Mitchell Starc got rid of the dangerous Tagenarine Chanderpaul. They are now just six wickets away from their win.

Hello and a warm welcome for the Day 4 of the West Indies tour of Australia. The hosts are dominating the game since Day 1 and the visitors are dwelling at 38/4 and needing 459 more runs to win. Aussies just need six wickets in the game and they will be looking to get some early wickets in the game.
... DAY 4, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, West Indies only have 6 wickets in hand but the target is a steep one. They need a miracle with the blade if they are to pull off a remarkable come back in this fixture. Australia will be aiming to end things as early as possible. Do join us on 11th December at 9.30 pm IST (4 am GMT). Until then, take care and goodbye!

West Indies already had a tough task on their hands chasing 497 runs, although it did not go as per plan.as they were teetering at 21/4 inside the first 10 overs. Later, Jason Holder and Devon Thomas played with grit and determination to not restrict a defeat on Day 3 itself. They still have a lot to bat and it won't be an easy task against a threatening Australian bowling attack.

The moving day was quite an enticing one and boy, did it not move at a rapid pace. Australia came out with the blade in the final session and came with an aggressive approach as they aimed to get 500 runs on the board. Although, it did not go as they envisioned and lost wickets at regular interval. They posted a target of 497 runs.
